For non-Latin scripts, correspondences are generally based, where possible, on their historical connections or phonetic/transcription values.<ref>[http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0014/001480/148088eb.pdf]</ref> For example, Greek γ ''gamma'' is written {{Braille cell|1245|type=text}} ''g'', as it is romanized, not {{Braille cell|14|type=text}} ''c'', as it is ordered in the alphabet or as it is related historically to the Latin letter ''c''. Occasional assignments are made on other grounds, such as Greek ω ''omega'', which is written {{Braille cell|2456|type=text}} ''w'', as in [[beta code]] and internet chat alphabets, due to the graphic resemblance of Latin ''w'' and Greek ''ω''.

