The 1878 congress only succeeded in unifying the basic Latin alphabet. The additional letters of the extended [[French braille]] alphabet, such as {{bc|⠯}}, are not included in the international standard.  The French {{bc|⠯}}, for example, corresponds to print {{angbr|ç}}, whereas the {{bc|⠯}} in English and German braille transcribes {{angbr|&}}, and the {{bc|⠯}} in Hungarian and Albanian braille is {{angbr|q}}.

===Alphabets limited to grade-1 braille===
{{anchor|Grade 1 braille}}Languages that in print are restricted to the letters of the [[ISO basic Latin alphabet|basic Latin script]] are generally encoded in braille using just the 26 letters of grade-1 braille with their French/English values, and often a subset of those letters.  Such languages include:
:[[Bemba language|Bemba]], [[Chewa language|Chewa]] (Nyanja), [[Dobuan language|Dobuan]], [[Greenlandic language|Greenlandic]],<ref>Greenlandic Braille also recognizes the additional letters of [[Danish Braille]], found in loan words or proper names.</ref> [[Huli language|Huli]], [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]], [[Luvale language|Luvale]], [[Malagasy language|Malagasy]], [[Malaysian language|Malaysian]], [[Southern Ndebele language|Ndebele]], [[Shona language|Shona]], [[Swahili language|Swahili]],<ref>Swahili also uses the apostrophe in ''ng’''.</ref> [[Swazi language|Swazi]], [[Tok Pisin]], [[Tolai language|Tolai]] (Kuanua), [[Xhosa language|Xhosa]], [[Zulu language|Zulu]].<ref name="unesco3">[http://www.pharmabraille.com/LiteratureRetrieve.aspx?ID=122064 World Braille Usage], UNESCO, 2013<br>All of these alphabets use traditional English Braille punctuation and formatting, except for Greenlandic, which follows [[Danish Braille]] conventions.<!--Unesco 2013 reports Malaysian Braille (but not Indonesian) uses a parenthesis, {{bc|2356}}, for the virgule, but this is not confirmed.--></ref>

In these languages, print digraphs such as ''ch'' are written as digraphs in braille too.

[[Philippine Braille|Languages of the Philippines]] are augmented with the use of the accent point with ''n'', {{bc|4|n}}, for ''ñ''.  These are [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]], [[Ilocano language|Ilocano]], [[Cebuano language|Cebuano]], [[Hiligaynon language|Hiligaynon]], and [[Bicol language|Bicol]]; ''Ethnologue'' reports a few others.

[[Zambian Braille|Languages of Zambia]] distinguish ''ñ/ŋ/ng’'' {{IPA|[ŋ]}} from ''ng'' {{IPA|[ŋɡ]}} with an apostrophe, as in Swahili Braille:  {{bc|n|g|3}} ''ng’'' vs {{bc|n|g}} ''ng''.  These are [[Lozi language|Lozi]], [[Kaonde language|Kaonde]], [[Lunda language|Lunda]], and [[Tonga language (Zambia)|Tonga]]. [[Ganda language|Ganda]] (Luganda) may be similar.<ref>Unesco (2013) claims Ganda Braille has a different point for ''ŋ'', {{bc|n|g|1}}, but that would make it a homograph with ''nga''.  It may thus be a copy error for the apostrophe used in Swahili and Zambia.</ref>

''Ethnologue'' 17 reports braille use for [[Mossi language|Mòoré]] (in Burkina Faso), [[Rwanda language|Rwanda]], [[Rundi language|Rundi]], [[Zarma language|Zarma]] (in Niger), and [[Luba-Sanga language|Luba-Sanga]], but provides few details.

==Congress of 1929==
In 1929 in Paris, the American Foundation for Overseas Blind sponsored a conference on harmonizing braille among languages which use the Latin script, which had diverged in the previous decades.

==Congresses of 1950–1951==
When additional letters are needed for a new braille alphabet, several remedies are used. 
# They may be borrowed from an existing alphabet; French–German {{bc|type=t|ä}} ''ä'', {{bc|type=t|ö}} ''ö'', and {{bc|type=t|ü}} ''ü'', for example, are widely used where a language had need of a second a-, o-, or u-vowel. Likewise, the values of English contracted ("Grade 2") {{bc|type=t|ch}} ''ch'', {{bc|type=t|sh}} ''sh'', and {{bc|type=t|th}} ''th'' are widely used for similar sounds in other languages.
# An otherwise unused letter may be reassigned. For example, [[Tibetan Braille]], which is based on German Braille, reassigns {{bc|type=t|c}} ''c'', {{bc|type=t|q}} ''q'', {{bc|type=t|x}} ''x'', and {{bc|type=t|y}} ''y'', which are redundant in German.
# In the case of [[diacritic]]s in the print alphabet, a point may be added to the base letter in braille. [[Latvian Braille]], for example, adds dot 6 to indicate a diacritic, at the cost of abandoning several international assignments.
# New letters may be invented by modifying a similar letter. Modification may be done through moving the letter (thus {{bc|type=t|en}} and {{bc|type=t|in}} for a second ''e'' or ''i'' vowel), stretching the letter (again, {{bc|type=t|ch}} and {{bc|type=t|st}} for ''e''- and ''i''-like vowels), or rotating or reflecting it. The latter is quite common, producing such pairs as {{bc|type=t|s}} ''s'' – {{bc|type=t|wh}} ''sh'' and {{bc|type=t|n}} ''n'' – {{bc|type=t|ed}} ''ny''. See [[Hungarian Braille]] for an alphabet which has exploited a pattern of mirror images, and [[Thai Braille]] for the series {{bc|type=t|v}} บ ''b'', {{bc|type=t|ç}} ป ''p'', {{bc|type=t|p}} ผ ''ph<sub>1</sub>'', {{bc|type=t|th}} พ ''ph<sub>2</sub>''.

A regional UNESCO conference on braille uniformity for southern Asia took place in 1950.<ref>[http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0014/001478/147828eb.pdf]</ref> This led to a conference with global scope the following year. The 1951 congress found many conflicting braille assignments:

:"Most Asian and African languages contain more letters or sounds than Roman had equivalents for, [and] they had to find some way of representing them. Most of the designers of Braille spoke English and some of them turned to the contractions of English Braille to find signs which would provide precedents for local letter values ... But beyond these again, many non-European alphabets included letters for which no Braille precedent had been created. Arbitrary signs had to be allotted to them, with the consequence that even throughout these traditional Brailles only limited uniformity was achieved."<ref>Unesco, 1953, pp 27–28</ref>

The congress recognized the role of English contracted braille in establishing a partial international standard, and recommended that alphabets follow existing conventions as much as possible.

===Common extended correspondences===
